    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "Section 3: Navigation & Information Architecture",
      "description": "The navigation model conflates linear browser history with hierarchical drill-down semantics. The spec describes tabs as 'parallel peer destinations' yet implements them as hash routes that push history entries. If a user flows Home → Detail (drill-down) → Search (tab switch), the history stack becomes [#/, #/doc/123, #/search]. Pressing Back from Search returns to Detail (a dead end) rather than Home, violating the tab paradigm where switching tabs should replace, not push, state. This creates a 'history trap' where users cannot efficiently switch between primary sections without backtracking through drill-down contexts.",
      "suggested_fix": "Implement history.replaceState() for all tab switches (Home/Search/Library), ensuring the browser history reflects only the drill-down hierarchy, not tab context switches. Document explicitly: tabs are persistent UI state, not history entries."
    },
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "Section 3: Drill-down views and Section 4: DetailScreen",
      "description": "Deep linking directly to #/doc/:id presents a broken back navigation affordance. The Detail screen displays a chevron-left 'Back' button, but when accessed directly (shared link, refresh), window.history.length === 1 and there is no parent to return to. The spec provides no fallback behavior (e.g., redirect to Home, or swap 'Back' for 'Close'), leaving users stranded in a dead-end view.",
      "suggested_fix": "Detect direct entry (history.state === null or history.length === 1) in DetailScreen. When detected, replace the 'Back' button with a 'Home' link (href='#/') and skip the history.back() call. Alternatively, inject a synthetic Home entry into the stack before the detail route on direct entry."
    },
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "Section 6: Data fetching and Section 4: Screen components",
      "description": "The 'fetch-on-mount' pattern combined with conditional route rendering (route → Screen component) guarantees state loss on tab switching. When a user scrolls through Search results, switches to Library, then returns to Search, SearchScreen unmounts and remounts, destroying scroll position, input text, and fetched results. This 'pogo-sticking' penalty makes cross-reference workflows (comparing items across tabs) unusable.",
      "suggested_fix": "Implement the 'Persistent Tab Panel' pattern: render all three tab screens simultaneously in the DOM, using CSS (display: none or visibility/opacity with inert) to show/hide, rather than conditional rendering. This preserves component state and scroll position. Alternatively, hoist Search state to the Router context and implement scroll restoration via sessionStorage, though this is more fragile."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "Section 3: Search presets and Section 5: searchDocuments",
      "description": "The synchronization between search input state and URL query parameters (?q=) is undefined. If the user types a manual query (not using presets), the URL does not update, making the search non-shareable and vulnerable to refresh data loss. If the implementation updates the URL on input, it risks polluting history with every keystroke (unless using replaceState). The spec mentions presets set the query param but omits the manual typing behavior entirely.",
      "suggested_fix": "Specify that SearchScreen uses history.replaceState (not pushState) to sync the ?q= parameter as the user types (debounced at 300ms). This ensures shareability without history pollution. Explicitly ban pushState for input-driven updates."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "Section 3: Bottom tab bar and Section 7: Design tokens",
      "description": "The fixed bottom tab bar lacks safe area handling for iOS Safari (env(safe-area-inset-bottom)), guaranteeing that the tab bar will be obscured by the browser's native bottom bar or cause accidental home bar interactions. Additionally, the spec omits pull-to-refresh behavior, a mandatory mobile interaction pattern for content feeds.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add --safe-bottom: env(safe-area-inset-bottom) to tokens.css and apply padding-bottom: var(--safe-bottom) to the TabBar container. Specify pull-to-refresh implementation: use overscroll-behavior-y: contain on the main scroll container and implement a pull-to-refresh hook that triggers on negative scroll with resistance."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "Section 3: Bottom sheet",
      "description": "Focus management on sheet close assumes the trigger element remains mounted and visible. If the trigger was inside a virtualized list (Timeline, Results) and the user scrolled, the element may be unmounted from the DOM or recycled. Calling .focus() on a detached element throws or sends focus to body, breaking keyboard navigation flow.",
      "suggested_fix": "Before returning focus, check triggerRef.current?.isConnected. If false, fall back to focusing the screen container (document.querySelector('[role=main]')) or the first focusable element in the new visible set."
    }
  ],
  "suggestions": [
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "Section 4: Component Architecture",
      "description": "Add an 'IA Guard' component that monitors route changes and enforces the 'tabs replace history' rule, logging violations in development. This prevents future developers from accidentally using pushState in tab handlers."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "Section 7: tokens.css",
      "description": "Add semantic motion tokens for 'exit' vs 'enter' durations. Currently only generic durations are defined. Drill-down transitions should be faster (200ms) than sheet entrances (300ms) to reinforce the hierarchy."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "Section 0: Pre-Migration Audit",
      "description": "Explicitly map the 404 handling behavior for API routes to the ErrorState component variants. Distinguish between 'endpoint not found' (dev error) and 'resource not found' (valid 404), as they require different UX (retry vs 'item deleted')."
    }
  ],
